text: Okay for those bitching about Annie being black, let me explain you a thing. This is supposed to be a modern remake, the original Annie had red hair to imply that she was Irish, the Irish were looked down upon and there was a lot of prejudice against people of Irish descent. So This Annie is black because nowadays being Irish isn't really an issue regarding repression and discrimination, it doesn't make you less likely to be adopted or get you treated badly or leave you the victim of inequalities. However, despite most people claiming they are not racist, racism particularly towards black people in America is a large problem, you are also much less likely to be adopted if you are a black LAC (Looked After Child). So this is why Annie in this modern remake is not red haired or Irish, simple. If you still think Annie being cast this way is a problem after reading why then you're probably racist so stop leaving racist comments here and start commenting on UKIP videos instead with your other bigoted and small minded friends.

text: Who says that once a film is made.  That's it.  It Has to be set in stone?   Who makes these "rules" up? Art is art.  Film is art.   Why the hell not make a modern remake and Have Someone else's take on the fictional story? The original Annie was set in the 1930's.  Not the most friendliest time for people of color.   Orphanages or group homes today have diversity and I'm sure the younger generation want to be represented in film/tv.   I think it's a story that can be updated and adapted to suit the times we are living in.  A modern multicultural society.   I think those of you are having a fit over a little girl of a different race playing Annie are all ridiculous and need to get over it.  And  really consider why you think the original is "classic" and it shouldn't be remade.  Why is that?  You haven't even seen the new version yet and oppose it. Can't stand change? Possibly white?  You Can't handle the idea of a little brown girl playing Annie.   Oh the horror of it all.  But,  but she's not white nor got red hair.   So what?   I bet most of you wouldn't be so irate if the remake had a white girl with blonde hair.  You'd probably find some reason to make THAT ok.    Annie can be played by ANY little girl with any  skin or hair color who has the right acting and singing skills.   I'm rooting for the movie to be a success.   Bah humbug!  to all of you who oppose the new Annie remake.

text: ".... If you grew up all all your life knowing that the character of Annie is & was white , even before you were born that Annie has always been written & portrayed¬†as a white character & all of a sudden you go to the movies now¬†& watch Annie as a black girl , this impostor , it really doesn't allow yourself to get deeply involved into the movie. It just doesn't fit the mold or fall into place because you know in the back or even thr front of your mind that you know Annie as & always will be portayed as¬†a white girl & all of a sudden , no matter how much you try to force yourself to be open minded that Annie is somehow a black gil now , your mind will not allow yourself to get into that mode of involvement. Your brain knows better than that. You have trained your brain to know that Annie is & always will be a white girl character no matter how much you want to change it for a couple of hours. My knowing for all my life that Annie is a white girl & all of a sudden¬†I am supposed to go with the pretend idea that Annie is black does not jibe with what I have always known & have seen her as a white girl all my life growing up. No way can I fool my brain into watching this movie & seriously allowing my brain to be open to Annie being a white girl when all I can picture in my mind is the original 1982 movie of Aileen Quinn being the one & only one to play Annie. To force your mind to see a black girl play a white girls movie part is impossible knowing what you have known all your life as a black girl playing a white girl's part. It has nothing to do with racism. It has to do with what you have known all your life from childhood¬†& what your mindset of your ¬†brain is trained in knowing visually & how the books are written & told as it's being depicted for going on 32 years now. You cannot fool or trick or manipulate your brain into thinkikng or knowing that Annie is a¬†black girl all of a sudden. There is no way you can wrap your mind around Annie being portrayed by a black girl knowing what you have known all your life growing up as Annie being none other than a white girl. Common sense & knowing better will not allow your mind to sit through a movie with a black girl playing Annie¬†knowing what you know going through your entire life knowing that reading cartoon books or comic books & stories about Annie being addressed as a white character. I don't know of anyone who can convince their mind that Annie is now a black character knowing what it knows for all this time that Annie is & was written & depicted as a white girl based character. To think anyone can trick their minds into getting deeply involved in this movie seriously as Annie as a black girl knowing what they know of Annie being a white girl character¬†is just being naive. When your brain knows for decades or all your life that Annie is a white girl & this crap comes along ,¬†your brain starts to parent you into telling you to get real. text: After spending some time in the comments I've realized that racist can also be used synonymously with idiot. When racist people make their stand their is no point in arguing with them. They will make their decision on their stance and use the most ludicrous of examples to prove their point.  A lot of the commenters are stating that this movie shouldn't be remade with a black person and using the pretense that africans wouldn't like if "roots" (the most common example I saw) was remade using white people.   Roots.  Yes people. Roots.  They want a white man to play a slave, but they want black people to actually be the slaves for hundreds of years.  Roots Is a movie that represents a snapshot in time with distinctive rolls that must be maintained in order to not break the authenticity or immersion. (Similar reasoning can be used for the exodus movie.)  Annie is a character.  Created in a comic book. Her main characteristics that define her do not have a specific race attached. There are Orphans of all races in America. When you think orphan do you think of a specific race? Now when you think slave what comes to mind?  The answer to those two questions is obvious. They answered it in the exodus movie where all, or most of the Slave roles were inhabited by black people.  Yes, I do understand that Annie was very much characterized by her red hair, but you must under stand this is a remake that takes place In a different time period. The main plot lines and character rolls are what's important not physical characteristics, however Exodus and Roots are movies that take place in their original time.  Comparisons between the two and their casting decisions can not be made, unless you are a racist idiot simply looking to prove a foolish point.

text: The reason they made her black was to continue the symbol that Annie originally portrayed with her red hair. Back with the original Annie, Irish decedents were shown as undesirables, thus Annie's red hair and freckles. Now that we have a modern Annie, they wanted to continue the metaphor of racism in the city and casted her as African American. It's a choice they made to reflect today's view on orphans in the city, compared to how orphans used to be seen.¬†

author: Janice Thomas

text: I watched this film at the persistent requests of my three daughters. I went into it thinking it was going to be awful. Like, I really *wanted* to hate it because (A) I'm a dude, (B) I am getting sick of all the constant remakes, and (C) I was afraid the race change would end up just being a gimmick for the purpose of drawing in a wider audience. Then I watched it...and to my surprise, I did NOT hate it. I actually rather liked it. Sure, it wasn't the original. But it didn't try to be. It was a nice re-imagining of the story, not just a re-telling. It didn't come off as "forced". There was diversity without being heavy-handed or insulting‚Äîit wasn't steeped in stereotypes or a "Hey, white people‚Äîyou suck" message. The music takes some liberties from the original classics, but they fit this new version. Quvenzhan√© Wallis has a lot of heart, and Jamie Foxx and Rose Byrne are great in their roles. They do a good job of making you "feel" the characters.  If you haters really want to get butt-hurt, go watch Disney's craptastical 1999 TV-movie version. My girls forced me to sit through it, and THAT one was a schlocky piece of garbage.
